\par \pard\plain \s10\li120\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 Leash is a user interface for Kerberos on MS-Windows, which you can use to obtain Kerberos tickets and to change your Kerberos password.
\par 
\par Leash combines the functionality of several commands available in MIT's Athena environment. On Athena a user would use {\uldb kinit}{\v ID_HELP_KINIT}, {\uldb klist}{\v ID_HELP_KLIST}, {\uldb kdestroy}{\v ID_HELP_KDESTROY}, passwd or kpasswd, and {\uldb 
kerberometer}{\v ID_HELP_METER}. Leash combines all of these functions into one user interface and also supports {\uldb Dash-style notification}{\v ID_HELP_METER} to the user when tickets are nearing their expiration.
\par 
\par During the next two years MIT's DCNS expects to release several applications for use at MIT that will use Kerberos authentication. These include TechMail for Windows and DOS, TechInfo for Windows, OLxx for Windows, Zephyr, Discuss, and remote printing ser
vices. Other MIT departments may also be creating applications that use Kerberos, and we expect Leash to complement these applications as well.
\par 
\par You may wish to add Leash to your Windows start-up group. When doing so,
 use the Properties menu in the Program Manager to tell Windows to run Leash iconified. When Windows starts up, you will be prompted for your Kerberos username and password. Leash then obtains a Kerberos ticket for you. Thus, when you start up any other K
erberized applications--such as TechMail for Windows--you will not be prompted for your password a second time.
\par 
\par Without Leash in your start-up group and without running it before using a Kerberized application, the application normally prompts you for yo
ur password. Some applications, like lpr, never prompt you for a password. These applications simply terminate with a message indicating that you are not authenticated. For these applications you must use a separate program to perform the authentication: 
The program to use is Leash.
\par \pard\plain \s254\li115\sb80\sl-240 \b\f3\lang1033 {\plain \f3\lang1033 
\par }{\plain \f3\fs20\lang1033 Leash is not a real log-in program, which would do much more than Leash. A real log-in program helps to verify the integrity of your local disk system and performs additional set-up tasks. These are beyond the scope of Leash.}
{\plain \f3\fs20\lang1033  Leash simply allows you to obtain Kerberos tickets and to change your Kerberos password. }{\plain \f3\lang1033 
\par }\pard\plain \s10\li120\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
