\par \pard \s10\li120\sl-240 {\b How To Use Change Password...}
\par \pard\plain \fi-600\li720\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\b 1.}\tab In Leash, click on the Change Password button, type your username in the first field of the dialogue box that opens, and press Enter or click OK.
\par \pard \li720\sb80\sl-240 {\b Note}:\tab You may start over anytime by clicking Restart. 
\par \pard \fi-600\li720\sb80\sl-240 {\b 2.}\tab Type your {\i current} password in the second field and press Enter or click OK.
\par \pard \li720\sb80\sl-240 {\b Result}:\tab The program checks the username and password you entered and notifies you if either is invalid.
\par \pard \fi-600\li720\sb80\sl-240 {\b 3.}\tab Type your {\i new} password in the third field and press Enter or click OK.
\par {\b 4}.\tab Retype your {\i new} password, to verify it, and press Enter or click OK.
\par \pard \li720\sb80\sl-240 {\b Result}:\tab Once you have entered the new password twice with consistent spellings, the Leash program replaces your old password with the new, {\i if it is a strong password. }
If Kerberos determines the password is weak, a message notifies you, and you need to{\i  }repeat steps 1 through 4 with a strong password, as described by the "How To Choose a Password" guidelines above.
\par \pard \li120\sb80\sl-240 
\par \pard\plain \s254\li115\sl-240 \b\f3\lang1033 {\fs20 To Close Change Password...}{\fs20 
\par }{\plain \f3\fs20\lang1033 At any time you can click the Cancel button to close the Change Password dialog box (without making changes) and r}{\plain \f3\fs20\lang1033 eturn to the main Leash window.}{\plain \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par }\pard\plain \s10\li120\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par {\b How Change Password Works...}
\par \pard\plain \li115\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
When you type into the password fields of the dialog box, neither characters nor sounds echo back, thus keeping secret even the number of password characters. The program accepts only printable characters for new passwords, i.e., characters between ASCII 
codes 0x20 and 0x7E.
\par 
\par \pard \li90\sb80\sl-240 When you have entered the new password twice consistently, the program attempts to change the password via a dialogue with the Kerberos administrative server. Some Kerb
eros sites, including MIT's Athena environment, check the password's strength before allowing the change to take place and notifies you if it determines that the password is weak.{\fs18 
\par }\pard \li115\sl-240 
