\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 From I/S Newsletter
\par Vol. 8, No. 7
\par 
\par Computer passwords are like keys: they are a way to control access to machines and the files and programs on them. You may use passwords for e-mail, to connect to local computers and servers, or to access computers over a network. To ensure the security o
f your passwords, it's important to change them often - at lea
st twice a year. This is especially important for networked computers. Some systems, such as the MITVMA/C mainframes, force you to change your password every 90 days; other systems, such as Athena, expect you to take the initiative.
\par 
\par {\b What's a Good Password?}
\par When you create or change a password, aim for something easy to remember, yet obscure. You might combine two words, use a combination of letters and numbers, or choose a phrase like "many colors" and then misspell it (e.g., mnYc0l0rz). Your password shoul
d be at least six characters long.
\par If you have multiple accounts on one or more computers, use a different password for each account. Note: Athena and TechMail, along with other MIT network programs, rely on Kerberos authentication. If you have an Athena a
nd a TechMail account, the password is the same for both. 
\par 
\par {\b What Not To Do}
\par When choosing a password, don't use your license plate number, social security number, or other public number. Don't pick a password that is all numbers. Don't choose dictionary words, names associated with you, or names from popular culture, such 
as Sleepy, Zaphod, or Spock. Never tell anyone your passwords - not even IS staff - and don't write them down. If you forget your Athena password, go to Athena User Accounts, Room 11-124H, and they will help you set up a new one. If you forget your passwo
rd on MITVMA/C, call Client Services at x3-7230. On other systems, contact the system administrator.
\par 
