\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 In Greek myth, the three-headed dog Kerberos guarded the gates of Hades. These days, {\i Kerberos} is an {\uldb authentication}{\v ID_HELP_AUTHENTIC}
 service developed at MIT for open network computing environments such as MITnet. {\i Kerberos} verifies that you are who you claim to be by matching your username and password, called a {\i Kerberos} {\uldb principal}{\v ID_HELP_PRINCIPAL}
, to a private key encryption. 
\par When you start an application that relies on {\i Kerberos} authentication, you must identify yourself by giving your {\i Kerberos} principal. The {\i Kerberos} service checks to make sure that your name and password match the encrypted key be
fore it gives you access to the service you have requested. The security of the network environment is maintained by never sending your unencrypted {\i Kerberos} password over the network. 
\par To use the Athena system, you must have a {\i Kerberos} username and password. Some Macintosh and DOS applications at MIT that use {\i Kerberos} to authenticate a user's identity are TechMail, TechInfo (provider functions only), Discuss, and Zephyr.

