\par \pard\plain \s254\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320 \b\f3\lang1033 \page {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Kerberos Tickets}} {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} ID_HELP_TICKETS}} Kerberos Tickets
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par When you authenticate yourself with Kerberos, through either the Leash program or the kinit command, Kerberos gives you an initial Kerberos ticket. (A Kerberos ticket is an encrypted protocol message that provides authentication.) Kerberos uses this ticke
t for network utilities such as TechMail or TechInfo. The ticket transactions are done transparently, so you don't have to worry about their management.
\par 
\par Note, however, that tickets expire. Privileged tickets, such as root instance tickets, expire in a few minutes, while tickets that carry more ordinary privileges may be good for several hours or a day, depending on the installation's policy. If your log-i
n session extends beyond the time limit, you will have to re-authenticate yourself to Kerberos to get new tickets.
\par 
\par {\b See Also}
\par \pard \li360\sb80\sl-240 {\uldb An Authentic}{\uldb ation Service}{\v ID_HELP_USENIX88}
\par {\uldb How Does the Other Guy Know Who I Am?}{\v ID_HELP_SIPB}
\par \pard\plain \s254\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320 \b\f3\lang1033 \page {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Kerberos Names}} {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} ID_HELP_NAMES}} Kerberos Names
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par A Kerberos name contains three parts. The first is the principal name, which is usually a user's
 or service's name. The second is the instance, which in the case of a user is usually null. Some users may have privileged instances, however, such as ``root'' or ``admin''. In the case of a service, the instance is the name of the machine on which it ru
ns; i.e. there can be an {\b rlog-in}
 service running on the machine ABC, which is different from the rlog-in service running on the machine XYZ. The third part of a Kerberos name is the realm. The realm corresponds to the Kerberos service providing authenticati
on for the principal. For example, at MIT there is a Kerberos running at the Laboratory for Computer Science and one running at Project Athena.
\par 
\par When writing a Kerberos name, the principal name is separated from the instance (if not null) by a period, and the realm (if not the local realm) follows, preceded by an ``@'' sign. The following are examples of valid Kerberos names:
\par \pard \li2160\sb80\sl-240 billb
\par jis.admin
\par srz@LCS.MIT.EDU
\par treese.root@ATHENA.MIT.EDU
\par \pard\plain \s254\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320 \b\f3\lang1033 \page {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Leash Screen Display (Kerberometer and Dash Notification)}} {\plain 
\f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} ID_HELP_METER}} Leash Screen Display (Kerberometer and Dash Notification)
\par \pard\plain \s10\li120\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
For each set of Kerberos tickets, the main Leash program screen displays information about their current status, including the time that they were issued and the time that they will expire. At the top right, directly above the Leash icon, the {\b 
Kerberometer} displays your tickets' remaining time in hours, minutes, and seconds.
\par When you minimize the Leash window (reduce it to an icon), the icon displays the countdown timer for your ticket lifetime above the program name "Leash." On color screens, the icon background changes to indicate your tickets' viability:
\par \pard \li2160\sb80\sl-240 green = normal
\par yellow = tickets are within 15 minutes of expiration
\par red = tickets have expired, or you have no tickets
\par \pard \li120\sb80\sl-240 At 15, 10, and 5 minutes before your Kerberos tickets expire, you receive{\b  dash-style notification} -- a screen pops up to warn that your Kerberos tickets will expire soon and to give you the opportunity to renew them.
\par \pard\plain \s254\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320 \b\f3\lang1033 \page {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Kerberos:  How does the other guy know who I am?}} {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 
#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} ID_HELP_SIPB}} {\i Kerberos}: How Does the Other Guy Know Who I Am?
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par A portion of the text below was copied with permission from {\i An Inessential Guide to Athena} (5th edition) published by the Student Information Processing Board.
\par \pard \qc\li120\sb80\sl-240 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sb120 \fs20\lang1033 Athena has developed a system known as {\i Kerberos} to provide for security on a physically insecure network. A complete description of the mechanisms used by {\i Kerberos}
 to provide this security is beyond the scope of this document. This section describes why {\i Kerberos} is necessary in the Athena environment, the theory behind {\i Kerberos}
 (with pointers to further information), and the user commands which interface to {\i Kerberos}. It also gives hints for using {\i Kerberos} more effectively.
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sb120 \fs20\lang1033 {\b Why} {\i Kerberos} {\b is }{\f3\fs18\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} ID_HELP_AUTHENTIC}}{\f3\fs18\up6  }{\b needed}
. Most moderately-sized to large computer systems use some form of password protection scheme to {\i authenticate }users; that is, they require a user who wishes to log in to give both his name and a secret password which only he and the computer system
 know. Anyone who happens to know the password can claim to be that user. It is therefore desirable to prevent people from listening in on the conversation between the computer and the user's terminal or workstation.
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sb120 \fs20\lang1033 
This is relatively easy in the case of terminals directly connected to the machine, since each terminal has its own cable. In a local-area network, several (typically between 10 and 200) computers share one cable, and any computer can listen in on any net
work traffic. With the advent of netw
ork monitoring packages for IBM PC's and similar machines, it is relatively easy for a determined user to set up a program to listen in on a network for any and all passwords being sent over. This would allow an intruder to masquerade as someone else, vio
lating their privacy and perhaps stealing information (academic or otherwise). {\b Note that THE ELECTRONIC COMMUNICATIONS PRIVACY ACT of 1986 makes this a Federal crime} punishable by lots of nasty stuff (ask your lawyer for details).
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sb120 \fs20\lang1033 In addition, since Athe
na uses a workstation-based model of computation, with most operations taking place on a single-user workstation with occasional requests (for files, etc.) going to other "server" machines, Athena needed to set up some way to allow users to {\i prove}
 their identity to such server machines.
\par 
\par {\b A few definitions}. Knowledge of the following terms is not essential for use of {\i Kerberos} but is helpful in understanding what is going on:
\par \pard \s19\fi-1440\li1440\sb120 {\b user:}\tab 
A human being who wishes to use a computer system. A user, through his workstation, may make a series of requests to several servers in the course of a session, and would like to avoid (due to sheer laziness, among other things) having to type his passwor
d to each machine in question.
\par {\b service:}\tab A program or set of programs running on a computer which is accessible over the network. The service would like to know with certainty that the workstation to which it is providing the service is really being used by the {\b user}
 who claims to be logged in on the workstation. Note that workstations are {\i not }services, and thus one may not use {\i Kerberos} to log into them over the network.
\par {\f3\fs18\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} ID_HELP_PRINCIPAL}}{\f3\fs18\up6  }{\b principal:}\tab 
An entity which can both prove its identity and verify the identities of other principals who wish to communicate with it; each {\b user} and each {\b service} registered with {\i Kerberos} is thus a principal.
\par {\b ticket:} \tab A block of data which, when given to a user, enables him to prove his identity to a service. In the Athena environment tickets are stored in files in the {\i /tmp}
 directory, and are automatically erased on log-out. On DOS and Windows tickets are stored in RAM in an area of memory reserved by the program Kerbmem. They are automatically erased when the computer is rebooted or when the user issues the destroy tickets
 command from Leash. They may also be destroyed from DOS by typing kdestroy. They contain information which must be considered private to the user, and thus the file should be kept at protection mode 700
. As they contain a time stamp, they cease to be valid after eight hours. One ticket is needed for each service; tickets are used to build {\b authenticators}, which are sent over the network to the service.
\par {\b authenticator:} \tab 
A block of data which a user's workstation sends over the network to a specific service to prove that the workstation really is in use by that user. An authenticator expires after five minutes. One authenticator is typically built per session of use of a 
service; once the service decodes the authenticator, it generally permits the user to operate for as long as she wants. This behavior is not in any way mandated by the {\i Kerberos}
 suite of programs and libraries (it is just a detail of the implementation), but it is convenient and considered secure enough for the Athena environment.
\par \pard \s19\sb120 
\par {\b How It Works...}{\b 
\par }{\i Kerberos} uses a standard encryption-based authentication technique with a few variations designed to increase ease of use across administrative entities and reduce the number of possible "attacks" 
on the system. The system uses cryptographically sealed {\i tickets} and {\i authenticators}\} which may be passed over the network and decrypted only by a user or machine which knows the appropriate encryption/decryption key.
\par 
\par {\b Using }{\b\i Kerberos...}
\par Most of the programs in use with {\i Kerberos} are located in the standard user path. Some of the programs installed in the standard locations for 4.3BSD are actually versions of the programs converted to use {\i Kerberos}
, so that most of your interaction with {\i Kerberos} will be "under the covers'" and should not look or act any different than standard 4.3BSD.
\par 
\par {\b Registering with }{\b\i Kerberos}{\b ...}{\b 
\par }If you have an account registered with Athena, you are registered with {\i Kerberos}. If you do not have an Athena account, talk to the Athena Accounts Administrator at x3-1325 to either set up an Athena account or register with {\i Kerberos}.
\par 
\par Once registered with {\i Kerberos}, tickets are obtained by the log-in program every time you log into a workstation. You can also manually obtain new tick
ets (which you usually do only if your old ones have expired, 8 hours after you log in) by running the program{\f5  kinit}. It prompts for a username, requests an initial ticket from {\i Kerberos}
, and then asks for your password. If you are not registered with {\i Kerberos}, it will print{\f5  Principal unknown (Kerberos)}
. Unless you mistype your username, this should not happen. To correct this, or any other errors, contact a Consultant or the Athena Accounts Administrator.
\par \pard\plain \s254\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320 \b\f3\lang1033 {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 
\par }\page {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} How Kerberos Shares Tickets}} {\plain \f3\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #
} ID_HELP_SHARE_TICKETS}} How Kerberos Shares Tickets
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\b Why Do It...}
\par In the Athena environment Kerberos tickets are stored either on the local disk drive or in the workstation's memory. Tickets are obtained when the user logs into the Athena environment. Thus, during normal operation, users enter a password once only. On s
ome other platforms, however, the tickets are stored separately in each Kerberized application, and each time one of these Kerberized applications starts, the user must re-enter the password.
\par When the developers at Brown University began porting the Kerberos libraries to DOS and Windows, they elected to create a system that enables all applications to share Kerberos tickets. With this system {\i the user enters a password once only}
 for an entire suite of Kerberized applications. Thus, they created the program Kerbmem, whose first task is reserving memory for the ticket storage before trying to obtain tickets and before loading Windows.
\par (The Brown developers' second reason for developing Kerbmem is that they wanted to store Kerberos tickets in shared RAM memory on the PC; they wanted to avoid storing the tickets on the local disk since PCs are inherently insecure.)
\par \pard\plain \s10\li120\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\b 
\par }{\b How It's Done...}
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 The Kerbmem program comes with MIT's Network Services LAN WorkPlace distribution. Members of the MIT community may obtain a copy of LAN WorkPlace at no charge from the Network Help Desk. Please call 3-4101.

\par Running MIT's LAN WorkPlace installation program automatically installs Kerbmem as well as other network software. Kerbmem is copied to the \\net\\
kerb directory, which also contains the Kerberos configuration files and some DOS command line utilities for working with Kerberos tickets.
\par By default Kerbmem reserves 1 Kb of RAM for storing tickets. If you need more room to store tickets, you may pass Kerbmem a command line option to reserve more room.
\par If you need to remove Kerbmem from memory, first make sure that there are no TSR programs loaded above it. Then unload it by typing "kerbmem -u". It will tell you whether the unload is successful.
\par Kerbmem also sets an environment variable named KERBEROS_TICKETS. Users should not modify this variable! It is used by the Kerberos libraries and DLL to locate the storage space reserved for the tickets. Any modifications to the variable can make the syst
em unstable--in the {\i best} case you will not be able to recover the reserved memory until you reboot your machine.
