\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f3\fs20\lang1033 MIT's Distributed Computing and Network Services (DCNS) group adds two specialized capabilities to the applications they develop: Version Checking and the TestTracker.
\par {\b 
\par }{\b Version Checking: What Is It?}{\b 
\par }
Since most DOS and Macintosh programs are executed from a local disk rather than a centralized file server, DCNS developed Version Checking to let users know when new versions of their applications have been released. Because a version server machine is i
ntegral to Version Checking, applications with this capability are called "VS-enabled applications."
\par {\b How Does Version Checking Work?}{\b 
\par }
When a VS-enabled application starts up, it sends out a UDP packet to the machine named "versions." This packet queries "versions" about the application's version status by telling it some information about the application. In turn, "versions" checks its 
database and returns the appropriate status flag and data string (message to display to the user) to the requesting application. The table below lists the status flags that can be returned and the resulting actions of a VS-enabled application:
\par 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft12 \cellx1710\cellx5040\cellx9000\pard \sb80\sl-240\intbl {\b Status flag}{\b \cell }{\b Meaning}{\b \cell }{\b Application's response}{\b \cell }\pard \intbl {\b \row }\trowd \trgaph108\trleft12 \cellx1710\cellx5040\cellx9000
\pard \sb120\sl-240\intbl {\b up_to_date}\cell The user's application is current.\cell No action.\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard \sb120\sl-240\intbl {\b recommended}\cell 
The user's application is NOT current. DCNS recommends that the user obtain the current version.\cell Displays the associated message to the user; newer applications may display the message only occasionally.\cell \pard \intbl \row \trowd 
\trgaph108\trleft12 \cellx1710\cellx5040\cellx9000\pard \sb120\sl-240\intbl {\b required}\cell The user's application is NOT current. The user cannot run the application until obtaining the current version.\cell 
Displays the associated message to the user and then terminates; normally, the "required" flag is associated with a new application version only if running the "old" can affect network operations or cause the user catastrophic data loss.\cell \pard 
\intbl \row \pard \li120\sb80\sl-240 
\par {\b TestTracker: What Is It?}{\b 
\par }DCNS uses TestTracker to better determine how thoroughly an application has been tested by volunteer users/testers in the MIT community. TestTracker-enabled applications can register users/testers as a points of contact, and during alpha and beta tests
 the version server logs the usage of these applications.
\par During testing, DCNS may ask points of contact to perform specific tests or to report their observations of the application's behavior on their individual computers. The active participation of these testers helps DCNS to create more robust applications.

\par DCNS treats the usage information recorded in the server logs as confidential; the log is available to selected DCNS staff only. 
\par {\b How Does TestTracker Work?}{\b 
\par }
Much like the Version Checking capability, the TestTracker makes use of the machine "versions," as described above. When a user first starts a TestTracker-enabled application, it prompts for the user's name and contact information. The user has a number o
f options for registering:
\par \pard \fi-600\li720\sb80\sl-240 *\tab {\b Anonymously}: no name or point contact logged; the TestTracker database still logs the usage of the application.
\par *\tab {\b Full contact information}{\b .}
\par *\tab {\b Register this information for all applications}: selected information is written to the win.ini file. When started, the current application uses the information for the point of contact, and new TestTracker-enabled applications
, when first started, will not prompt the user for this information.
\par *\tab {\b Register this information for this application ONLY}: contact information is written into the ini file for the invoked application (and not into the win.ini file).
\par \pard \li120\sb80\sl-240 
\par {\b How to configure a VS-enabled application for use outside the MIT.EDU domain}{\b 
\par }Version server and TestTracker-enabled applications developed by MIT's DCNS query the machine "versions" by default, which works within the MIT.EDU domain. Other sites can set up their own version server computers: if the server has a cname of "versions,
" applications in the local domain will query that machine rather than the one at MIT; or an entry in the win.ini or application's ini file may be used to override the default hostname.
\par First check the contents of your win.ini file to see that it has a section tag that reads
\par \pard \li2880\sb80\sl-240 [Version Server / Test Tracker]
\par \pard \li120\sb80\sl-240 Under that section tag, perform one of the two actions from the table below:
\par 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft12 \cellx4320\cellx8640\pard \li120\sb80\sl-240\intbl {\b If you want}{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst {\b SYMBOL 188 }{\b \\}{\b f "Symbol"}}{\fldrslt }}{\b \cell }{\b do the following}{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst {\b SYMBOL 188 }{\b \\
}{\b f "Symbol"}}{\fldrslt }}{\b \cell }\pard \intbl \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft12 \cellx4320\cellx8640\pard \li115\sb120\sl-240\intbl all VS-enabled applications to query "versions.mit.edu" rather than "versions"\cell add {\b host=versions.mit.edu}
\cell \pard \intbl \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft12 \cellx4320\cellx8640\pard \li115\sb120\sl-240\intbl to specify the host to query for only specific applications\cell remove the [Version Server / Test Tracker] section tag from your win.ini file;
\par \pard \li120\sb80\sl-240\intbl insert the tag into the ini file for the individual application; and
\par add {\b host=versions.mit.edu}.\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard \li120\sb80\sl-240 
